		   <table class="mform"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform" valign="top">The next big secret<br clear=all>
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Thu, Sep 7th 3:19 PM 2000 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class=sm>IP: Logged</span> | <a href="/db/classes.html?class=2&mid=9683543815566&post=1"><a class=sm href="/db/classes.html?class=2&mid=9683543815566&num=4&page=&post=1&replyto=9683543815566"><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=11 width=17> Reply to this</a></a>   <a name=9683543815566></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=887"><span id=Sage>Zuranthium</span></a><b><span id=Sage><br>Sage</span></b><br><img src=/shared/user_star_ico.gif height=9 width=9><img src=/shared/user_star_ico.gif height=9 width=9><br>390 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [3.90]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Here is my next installment to these boards, from yours truly, Zuranthium. <br><br>CAUTION, IF YOU DON'T LIKE TO KNOW THE INNER WORKINGS OF EVERQUEST THEN DON'T READ THIS. YOU MAY COME OUT KNOWING SOME THINGS YOU DIDN'T WANT TO. DON'T SAY I DIDN'T WARN YOU. <br><br>This post will tell exactly how exp. in everquest works. Lets start out with the leveling formula. <br><br>The exp. needed to gain a level is: level * level * level * race * class * level multiplier <br><br>Here are the values for the races: <br><br>Troll:120, Iksar:120, Ogre:115, Barbarian:105, Wood Elf:100, High Elf:100, Erudite:100, Gnome:100, Half Elf:100, Dark Elf:100, Dwarf:100, Human:100, Halfling:95 . <br><br>Sorry guys, humans don't level faster than all the other races, contrary to popular belief. Halflings do by a minor amount. <br><br>Now here are the values for the classes: <br><br>Ranger:14, Shadowknight:14, Paladin:14, Bard:14, Monk:12, Enchanter:11, Necromancer:11, Magician:11, Wizard:11, Cleric:10, Shaman:10, Druid:10, Rogue:9.05, Warrior:9 . <br><br>As it turns out the hybirds(yes, bards...) take longer to level than the other classes. Warriors and rogues take the least exp. to level. <br><br>Finally, the last number to the formula, here are the level multipliers: <br><br>Levels 1-29: 1.0 , Levels 30-34: 1.1, Levels 35-39: 1.2, Levels 40-44: 1.3, Levels 45-49: 1.4 .....once you get to level 50 almost every level is a hell level and the multiplier steadily rises. <br><br>The 'hell' levels are caused by the sudden change in exp. needed to level at the first level of the level multiplier changes( ie 30, 35, 40, etc.). <br><br>So, lets have an example. We will use a Human Cleric. <br><br>At level 1 the cleric starts with no exp. and needs a total of 1 * 1 * 1 * 100 * 10 * 1 exp. to level, for a total of 1000 exp. and a difference of 1000 exp. <br><br>At level the the cleric starts with 1000 exp. he gained from level 1 and now needs 2 * 2 * 2 * 100 * 10 * 1 exp. to level, for a total of 8000 exp., and a difference of 7000 exp. <br><br>Now lets jump ahead some. At level 10 the cleric starts the level with 729,000 exp. from level 9 ( 9 * 9 * 9 * 100 * 10 * 1). At level 10 the cleric will need a total of 10 * 10 * 10 * 100 * 10 * 1 exp. to level....or 1,000,000 exp. Since he had already gained 729,000 exp. from previous levels, he needs to gain 271,000 exp. to get to level 11 ( 1,000,000 - 729,000 = 271,000 ). <br><br>At it contiues like this for a while until level 30, the first hell level. At level 29 the cleric needed to gain 2,437,000 exp. to level. Now at level 30 they need 30 * 30 * 30 * 100 * 10* 1.1 exp. to level...for a total of 29,700,000 exp. Since they already made 24,383,000 exp. from previous levels (29 * 29 * 29 * 100 * 10 * 1 = 24,389,000), they need to gain 5,317,000 exp. to level ( 29,700,000 - 24,383,000 = 5,317,000). <br><br>Now we will move on to how much exp. the creatures of the game give per kill. Every creature in the game gives level * level * type, of exp. per kill. <br><br>There are many type of creatures in the game....the type multiplier ranges anywhere from 75 to 110. There are 4 major types of creatures: <br><br>Newbie(levels 1-4): 100-110, Low(levels 5-6): 100, Outdoors(levels 7+): 75, Dungeon(any levels): 80. <br><br>If the mob casts or is overly powerful for its level, or is magical, then the type multiplier of that creature usually goes up some. So, the average level 1 mob gives 1 * 1 * 100 exp. per kill, for a total of 100 exp. That level 1 cleric would need to kill 10 level one things to advance to level 2. Knowing that, you can now calculate how many kills you need to level, or about how much exp. you would be able to earn over a period of time(3 hours for example). <br><br>Calculation group exp. isn't that hard. When in a group, the exp. for every kill is divided evenly between the the group members. There is no extra group exp. bonus. If anyone in the group is too low for the group, they will still be taking a share of exp. away from the group, however they will not gain it. If a group has a wide range of levels, but they are still all within the grouping level limit, a few odd things can occur. First of all if someone in the group kills something that cons blue to them, but green to another person int he group, they will have to share the exp. with the person(people) that conned it green, even though that higher level person won't get exp. for the kill. It will simply be wasted. <br><br>At higher levels green cons will still give exp. If they are one level green then they will give half the exp. that they normally would upon being killed. If they are two levels green they will give one quarter the exp. that they normally would. Anything that is 3 levels green or lower won't give any exp. <br><br>One of the last things is pets. While in groups pets will take absolutely NO exp. away from the group. No matter how many of them there are, they simply won't take any exp. away from the group. <br><br>In soloing situations it is a bit different. When soloing, the pet will take half of the exp. away from every kill IF they outdamage their master. If the person who is using the pet outdamages the pet with their spells, then the pet will take NO exp. away from the kill. That is why it is always very important to outdamage your pet if you are soloing. If you don't then you will lose a bunch of exp. that isn't going anywhere. <br><br>I think that about wraps it up. If you have any questions e-mail me at tim_gerber@yahoo.com , or just do a RE to this post. Hope you enjoyed it. use the information wisely. <br><br>Corpusnuntia/Divineshadow/Zuranthium/Plantmaster/naltec/Natalos/Sunsong <br><br>Player of many characters on the Nameless server. </p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >4 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
